---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const nppaBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Nurse Practitioner &amp; Physician Assistant Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Nurse practitioner and physician assistant mortgage from a lender who reads hospital W-2, specialty NP/PA tier, telehealth platform 1099, CRNA anesthesia partnership K-1, IDR-aware student loan DTI, and Physician/Doctor Loan extension as one income picture.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Working Nurse Practitioners (NPs &mdash; FNP, AGNP, PMHNP, PNP, WHNP, AGACNP, and other certifications) and Physician Assistants (PAs) carry a distinct mortgage qualifying file from physicians. <strong>Per BLS OOH May 2024 data, NPs run a median wage of $132,050 (top 10% $189,190) and PAs run $133,260 (top 10% $179,720), with substantial specialty premiums above median: Certified Registered Nurse Anesthetists (CRNAs) command $230K&ndash;$315K, dermatology NPs/PAs $185K&ndash;$280K, surgical PAs $165K&ndash;$220K, cardiology NPs/PAs $165K&ndash;$215K, hospitalist PAs $150K&ndash;$200K, emergency medicine PAs and aesthetic medicine NPs running variable but often six-figure ranges</strong>. Student loan burden runs $80K&ndash;$200K typical (substantially lower than MD/DO&rsquo;s $200K&ndash;$450K). Income mechanics include hospital W-2 employment as the dominant pattern, telehealth platform 1099-NEC income from Teladoc, Amwell, MDLive, Lemonaid, Hims/Hers, K Health, Talkspace, and specialty platforms, locum NP/PA agency work, moonlighting W-2 from secondary employers, and (for NPs in Full Practice Authority states + aesthetic medicine NPs + some primary care NP practice owners) S-corp practice income. Many specialty lenders extend Physician/Doctor Loan products to NPs and PAs with similar low-down structure and no PMI, though typically at lower maximum loan amounts than MD/DO programs.</p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Talk to Our Team</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how NP/PA qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in NP/PA hospital W-2, telehealth platform 1099, CRNA anesthesia K-1, multi-source APRN income, &amp; Physician Loan extension for nurse practitioner and physician assistant mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/4173251/pexels-photo-4173251.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Nurse practitioner reviewing patient information" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=NP+PA';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$132,050 / $133,260</div>
            <div class="stat-label">BLS OOH May 2024 median annual wage for U.S. Nurse Practitioners and Physician Assistants respectively (top 10% over $180K-$190K)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$230K-$315K</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Certified Registered Nurse Anesthetist (CRNA) compensation range &mdash; the highest-earning APRN role (BLS shows nurse anesthetist median $214,200)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$80K-$200K</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Typical NP/PA student loan burden (MSN/DNP for NPs, MS-PA programs for PAs &mdash; substantially lower than MD/DO at $200K-$450K)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">24 + DC</div>
            <div class="stat-label">States granting NPs Full Practice Authority (FPA) per AANP &mdash; affects entity ownership and practice independence options</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/4226140/pexels-photo-4226140.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Physician assistant working with patient" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=NP+PA';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies working Nurse Practitioners and Physician Assistants on the full income picture &mdash; <strong>hospital or clinic W-2 base salary under Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 as continuous employment income with 24-month average, NP/PA productivity-based or RVU bonus compensation where applicable as variable income under B3-3.1-01 with 24-month trending support, telehealth platform 1099-NEC income from Teladoc, Amwell, MDLive, Lemonaid, Hims/Hers, K Health, Talkspace, and specialty NP/PA-focused platforms aggregated as continuing Schedule C self-employment under B3-3.3-02, locum NP/PA 1099 work through specialty agencies, moonlighting W-2 from secondary hospital or clinic employers, CRNA W-2 plus partnership K-1 distributions for anesthesia group partners under B3-3.4-02, NP-owned aesthetic medicine practice S-corp distributions or PA-owned specialty practice S-corp distributions where applicable in Full Practice Authority states, hospital sign-on bonuses and loan-repayment-assistance for new-grad NPs/PAs in rural and underserved settings, signed forward employment contracts for new-grad NP/PA pre-start close under Physician/Doctor Loan extension programs at qualifying specialty lenders, $80K&ndash;$200K of federal student loans on income-driven repayment with actual servicer-statement payments counted in DTI under B3-6-05 instead of 1 percent of balance, and Public Service Loan Forgiveness eligibility for NPs and PAs employed at nonprofit hospitals</strong>. A new-grad FNP starting first hospital position post-MSN, an established hospitalist PA with telehealth supplementation, a CRNA in surgical group partnership with K-1 distributions, an aesthetic medicine NP practice owner, and a dermatology PA with specialty premium income each get qualified using methods that fit their actual structure. We pick the right door before we quote. Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other medical professional paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/medical-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">medical professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; NP &amp; PA mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every NP and PA should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Physician Loan extension</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Many Physician/Doctor Loan programs extend to NPs and PAs with similar low-down (0&ndash;10%) and no-PMI structure, typically capped at lower maximum loan amounts ($1M&ndash;$1.5M vs MD/DO $2M+ super-jumbo). For NPs and PAs in the typical $130K&ndash;$280K income range, the extended Physician Loan is often the optimal product.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">B3-6-05 IDR</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-6-05/monthly-debt-obligations" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-6-05</a>, actual IDR payment from <a href="https://studentaid.gov/manage-loans/repayment/plans/income-driven" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Federal Student Aid plans</a> counts in DTI. For NPs/PAs with $80K&ndash;$200K of debt on PAYE/SAVE/IBR, actual payments often run $100&ndash;$800/month vs $800&ndash;$2,000 under the 1% rule.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">AANP / AAPA</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The <a href="https://www.aanp.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">American Association of Nurse Practitioners (AANP)</a> represents NPs nationally. The <a href="https://www.aapa.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">American Academy of Physician Assistants (AAPA)</a> represents PAs. Both organizations track scope-of-practice law and specialty certification across states.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">State scope variation</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">NP independent practice authority varies by state: 24 states + DC grant Full Practice Authority (FPA) allowing NP-owned practice, 16 states grant Reduced Practice Authority requiring collaborative agreements, and 10 states grant Restricted Practice Authority. PA scope requires physician collaboration in all states but varies in specifics. State scope affects entity ownership possibilities.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your NP or PA career</div>
        <h2>NP and PA mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each stage of an NP or PA career has its own qualifying logic. A new-grad FNP starting first hospital position has a different mortgage path than an established hospitalist PA with telehealth supplementation, or a CRNA in surgical group partnership with K-1 distributions plus W-2 base.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">New-grad NP or PA (Years 1&ndash;2)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Just completed MSN/DNP (NP) or MS-PA program. Starting first hospital or clinic position. Sign-on bonus and loan-repayment-assistance ramping; $80K-$200K of MSN or PA-school student loans on IDR."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $100K&ndash;$140K W-2 first NP/PA position</li>
            <li>$80K&ndash;$200K student loans on PAYE or SAVE</li>
            <li>Hospital sign-on $5K&ndash;$30K + possible rural loan-repayment</li>
            <li>Conventional with B3-6-05 IDR OR Physician Loan extension</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See new-grad mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established hospital-employed NP or PA (Years 3&ndash;7)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established attending NP or PA at hospital, health system, or large clinic group. Possibly supplementing with telehealth platform 1099s or moonlighting W-2."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $130K&ndash;$200K W-2 + telehealth 1099 mix</li>
            <li>Telehealth platforms (Teladoc, Amwell, MDLive, Lemonaid, Hims/Hers)</li>
            <li>2-year history for telehealth 1099 supplementation</li>
            <li>Conventional Conforming or Jumbo with multi-source documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See established NP/PA mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">CRNA / specialty APRN tier</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Certified Registered Nurse Anesthetist or specialty-tier APRN (cardiology, dermatology, anesthesia). Higher income tier through specialty practice or partnership."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>CRNA income $230K&ndash;$315K (often hospital W-2 + call coverage)</li>
            <li>Anesthesia group partnership K-1 distributions where applicable</li>
            <li>Specialty NP/PA premiums $165K&ndash;$280K depending on field</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo or Physician Loan extension</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See CRNA / specialty mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Multi-source NP or PA</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"NP or PA combining hospital W-2 with substantial telehealth platform 1099, locum agency work, moonlighting at secondary hospital, or consulting income. Often mid-career with established multi-stream pattern."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $160K&ndash;$280K across multiple streams</li>
            <li>B3-3.1-01 W-2 + B3-3.3-02 1099 self-employment combined</li>
            <li>Locum NP/PA agencies (CompHealth, Locumtenens.com, NP Now)</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with multi-source documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See multi-source mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">NP/PA practice owner (FPA-state or specialty)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"NP-owned practice in Full Practice Authority state (primary care, mental health, aesthetic medicine, women&rsquo;s health) or PA-owned specialty practice (commonly aesthetic medicine). Often combines W-2 reasonable comp + K-1."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $200K&ndash;$500K through S-corp ownership</li>
            <li>S-corp W-2 reasonable comp + K-1 distributions under B3-3.4-02</li>
            <li>Aesthetic medicine NP/PA practice common in FPA states</li>
            <li>S-Corp Self-Employed Conventional with Form 1084 addbacks</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See practice owner mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your NP or PA mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every NP and PA file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on your career stage, whether you maintain hospital employment alongside other streams, the role of telehealth platform 1099 income, and whether you operate an NP/PA-owned practice in a Full Practice Authority state.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Hospital W-2 + IDR-aware DTI (the NP/PA default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for working NPs and PAs. Hospital, health system, or clinic W-2 base salary qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> as continuous employment income with 24-month average. NP/PA productivity bonus or RVU bonus where applicable (less universal than physician RVU but increasingly common in larger health systems) qualifies as variable income with 24-month trending. Hospital sign-on bonuses ($5K&ndash;$30K typical for NPs/PAs, smaller than physician range) and loan-repayment-assistance for rural and underserved settings (commonly $10K&ndash;$30K annually) qualify when contracted with continuation provisions. The Physician/Doctor Loan extension layer adds low-down structure and no PMI for many specialty lenders, capped typically at $1M&ndash;$1.5M maximum loan amount.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Multi-W-2 stack (hospital + moonlighting + telehealth W-2)</h3>
      <p>For NPs and PAs stacking multiple W-2 employments: primary hospital position plus moonlighting W-2 at a second hospital or clinic plus W-2 telehealth platform employment. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, each W-2 stream qualifies as continuing employment with 24-month average. Multi-W-2 stacking is particularly common for hospitalist PAs (block schedule allowing secondary employment), emergency medicine NPs/PAs (shift-based), and CRNAs (call coverage at multiple facilities).</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; Hospital W-2 + Telehealth/Locum 1099 self-employment</h3>
      <p>For NPs and PAs who supplement hospital W-2 with telehealth platform 1099-NEC work through Teladoc, Amwell, MDLive, Lemonaid, Hims/Hers, K Health, Talkspace, or specialty NP/PA-focused platforms and/or locum NP/PA agency work through CompHealth, Locumtenens.com, NP Now, and similar firms. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, the hospital W-2 qualifies with 24-month average. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a>, telehealth and locum 1099 income aggregates as continuing Schedule C self-employment with 2-year history. The combined picture often substantially exceeds the hospital W-2 alone, particularly for NPs and PAs with established multi-platform telehealth practice.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; CRNA partnership K-1 or NP/PA practice owner S-corp</h3>
      <p>For CRNAs in anesthesia group partnerships and for NP/PA practice owners (typically NPs in Full Practice Authority states running primary care, mental health, women&rsquo;s health, or aesthetic medicine practices; or PAs running aesthetic medicine or specialty consulting practices). Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, qualifying income combines S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation plus K-1 distributions from <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1120-s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1120-S</a> with 2-year history. For CRNA anesthesia partnerships using <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1065" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1065</a> partnership returns, K-1s from the partnership aggregate similarly. Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks recover practice equipment depreciation and Section 179 expensing.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/4173251/pexels-photo-4173251.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on an NP or PA file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income facts that show up consistently on working NP and PA files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore, mis-categorize, or refuse to apply correctly. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to read the multi-source NP/PA pattern, specialty tier positioning, state scope, and IDR documentation properly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Telehealth platform 1099 income (NPs/PAs are heavily represented)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Telehealth platforms heavily contract NPs and PAs as independent contractors. Platforms like Teladoc Health, Amwell, MDLive, Lemonaid, Hims/Hers, K Health (NP-focused), Talkspace (mental health PMHNPs/PAs), and specialty platforms (women&rsquo;s health, dermatology, urgent care) issue 1099-NECs. Per-platform telehealth 1099 commonly runs $20K&ndash;$80K annually with multi-platform stacking producing $50K&ndash;$200K of supplementary income. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, these aggregate as continuing self-employment with 2-year history.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">CRNA W-2 + anesthesia partnership K-1 distributions</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Certified Registered Nurse Anesthetists in anesthesia group partnerships commonly combine W-2 reasonable compensation plus K-1 distributions from <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1065" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Form 1065</a> partnership returns. Per <a href="https://www.aana.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">American Association of Nurse Anesthesiology (AANA)</a>, CRNAs are the dominant anesthesia providers in approximately 70% of rural and outpatient anesthesia settings. CRNA partnership K-1 income runs $50K&ndash;$200K on top of base. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, these aggregate.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Specialty NP/PA premium income tiers</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Specialty NPs and PAs commonly earn substantially above the BLS median. Dermatology NPs/PAs $185K&ndash;$280K, surgical PAs $165K&ndash;$220K (first-assist + RVU bonus structures), cardiology NPs/PAs $165K&ndash;$215K, hospitalist PAs $150K&ndash;$200K, emergency medicine PAs and aesthetic medicine NPs running variable but often well above median. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a>, specialty premium W-2 + productivity bonus qualifies as variable income with 24-month average.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Federal student loan IDR payment at $100-$800/month (B3-6-05)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">MSN/DNP (for NPs) and MS-PA programs leave graduating NPs and PAs with $80K&ndash;$200K of federal student loans typically on income-driven repayment. At NP/PA income, the IDR-calculated monthly payment commonly runs $100&ndash;$800/month vs the $800&ndash;$2,000 that 1% of balance imposes. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-6-05/monthly-debt-obligations" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-6-05</a>, the actual servicer-statement payment counts in DTI. This swings $150K&ndash;$400K of qualifying loan amount.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">NP-owned practice S-corp in Full Practice Authority states</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Per <a href="https://www.aanp.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">AANP</a>, 24 states + DC grant NPs Full Practice Authority allowing NP-owned practice without physician collaborator. Common NP-owned practice categories: primary care, family practice, mental health (PMHNP), women&rsquo;s health (WHNP), aesthetic medicine (FNPs with aesthetic certification). Practice S-corps generate W-2 reasonable compensation plus K-1 distributions under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.4-02</a>. Often a key income stream that generalist lenders miss.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Physician/Doctor Loan extension to NPs and PAs</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Many Physician/Doctor Loan programs extend to NPs and PAs with similar product structure (0&ndash;10% down, no PMI, IDR-friendly DTI, signed-contract qualifying) typically capped at lower maximum loan amounts than MD/DO programs ($1M&ndash;$1.5M extension vs $2M+ for physicians). For the typical NP/PA income tier ($130K&ndash;$280K), the extended product accommodates the typical loan amounts. Generalist lenders may not know which Physician/Doctor Loan programs extend to NPs/PAs &mdash; we navigate the specialty lender landscape.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; Match the program to your NP/PA situation</div>
