  <!-- ============ H2 #6: INDUSTRY CONTEXT ============ -->
  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Why this mortgage requires specialty expertise</div>
        <h2>The NP and PA mortgage in context: 6 forces shaping how APRNs and PAs qualify.</h2>
        <p>NP and PA mortgage qualifying sits at the intersection of the fastest-growing healthcare professions per BLS workforce projections, state-by-state NP independent practice authority variation, post-COVID telehealth platform proliferation, CRNA specialty positioning in surgical and obstetric anesthesia, the aesthetic medicine NP/PA practice ownership trend, and the broader physician shortage driving NP/PA scope expansion. Each force shapes what a working NP&rsquo;s or PA&rsquo;s qualifying picture looks like.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Force 1 &mdash; NP/PA workforce growth (fastest-growing healthcare professions)</h3>
      <p>Per <a href="https://www.bls.gov/ooh/healthcare/nurse-anesthetists-nurse-midwives-and-nurse-practitioners.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BLS OOH workforce projections</a>, Nurse Practitioner employment is projected to grow 38% from 2022 to 2032 &mdash; among the fastest-growing occupations in the U.S. Physician Assistant employment is projected to grow 27% over the same period. The driver: physician shortage combined with scope-of-practice expansion making NPs and PAs the dominant care delivery model in primary care, mental health, urgent care, and many specialty settings. The mortgage implication: NP/PA income tier supports robust mortgage qualifying, and lender market increasingly extends specialty products (Physician Loan extension, signed-contract qualifying) to these professions.</p>

      <h3>Force 2 &mdash; State NP independent practice authority variation</h3>
      <p>Per <a href="https://www.aanp.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AANP</a>, NP independent practice authority varies by state: 24 states + DC grant Full Practice Authority (FPA) allowing NP-owned practice without physician collaborator (Arizona, Colorado, Connecticut, Delaware, Hawaii, Idaho, Iowa, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Montana, Nebraska, Nevada, New Hampshire, New Mexico, New York, North Dakota, Oregon, Rhode Island, South Dakota, Utah, Vermont, Washington, Wyoming, DC, plus more recent additions); 16 states grant Reduced Practice Authority requiring collaborative agreements; 10 states grant Restricted Practice Authority requiring active physician supervision. The mortgage implication: NP-owned practice S-corp ownership and income mechanics are heavily state-dependent.</p>

      <h3>Force 3 &mdash; Post-COVID telehealth platform proliferation</h3>
      <p>The COVID-era telehealth expansion permanently reshaped NP and PA practice patterns. Major telehealth platforms heavily recruit NPs and PAs as independent contractors: Teladoc Health, Amwell, MDLive, Doctor on Demand, PlushCare, Lemonaid Health, Hims/Hers, K Health, Talkspace (mental health PMHNPs and PAs), Sesame, Brightside Health, and many specialty platforms. NPs and PAs often have less restrictive credentialing requirements than physicians on these platforms, accelerating onboarding. The mortgage implication: telehealth 1099 income is a standard supplementary stream that we routinely aggregate under B3-3.3-02 alongside hospital W-2.</p>

      <h3>Force 4 &mdash; CRNA specialty positioning in anesthesia</h3>
      <p>Per <a href="https://www.aana.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">American Association of Nurse Anesthesiology (AANA)</a>, Certified Registered Nurse Anesthetists are the dominant anesthesia providers in approximately 70% of rural and outpatient anesthesia settings, with growing presence in academic medical centers and ambulatory surgery centers. CRNA training requires a Master&rsquo;s or DNP in nurse anesthesia (transitioning to entry-level doctoral by 2025), critical care RN experience, and NBCRNA national certification. The mortgage implication: CRNA income tier ($230K-$315K typical) substantially exceeds general NP median, with anesthesia partnership K-1 distributions adding additional structure for CRNAs in private practice groups.</p>

      <h3>Force 5 &mdash; Aesthetic medicine NP/PA practice ownership trend</h3>
      <p>The aesthetic medicine market has seen substantial growth in NP and PA practice ownership over the past decade. In Full Practice Authority states, NPs commonly own aesthetic medicine practices (injectables, laser treatments, body sculpting) under appropriate state licensing. PAs operate aesthetic practices under physician collaboration agreements. Per <a href="https://www.americanmedspa.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AmSpa</a>, NPs and PAs represent a substantial share of med-spa providers and increasingly owner-operators. The mortgage implication: NP/PA-owned aesthetic medicine practices generate S-corp K-1 distributions under B3-3.4-02 alongside any hospital or clinic W-2 supplementation.</p>

      <h3>Force 6 &mdash; Physician shortage driving NP/PA scope expansion</h3>
      <p>The U.S. physician shortage projected by <a href="https://www.aamc.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AAMC</a> drives ongoing scope-of-practice expansion for NPs and PAs across specialty settings. The trend: NPs and PAs increasingly fill specialty roles in dermatology, cardiology, orthopedics, gastroenterology, emergency medicine, hospitalist medicine, and psychiatry. The economic effect: specialty NPs and PAs command premium income tiers ($165K-$280K) above the BLS median for general primary care NPs and PAs. The mortgage implication: specialty positioning matters for proper income tier documentation and qualifying.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

