          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for an NP or PA mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically: two years of complete federal 1040s with all schedules including Schedule C if applicable; if NP-owned practice S-corp owner, Form 1120-S returns with K-1s; if CRNA in partnership, Form 1065 returns with K-1s; all W-2s from primary hospital and any moonlighting; all 1099-NECs from telehealth platforms, locum agencies, consulting; current servicer statement showing actual IDR payment; 60 days of personal bank statements; state NP/PA licensure documentation; NP/PA national certification (NCSBN for NPs, NCCPA for PAs); employment contract showing base salary and any sign-on or loan-repayment provisions.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is a physician (MD/DO). How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">NP/PA + physician spouse households produce strong joint qualifying. Both files combine as co-borrowers with W-2s, productivity bonuses, K-1 distributions if practice partners, and IDR payments. The physician spouse&rsquo;s established attending W-2 typically drives the qualifying capacity, with NP/PA income adding $130K-$280K to the joint income picture. Combined households commonly qualify for $1.5M-$3M mortgages.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for NPs and PAs?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Base conventional rates are the same for NPs and PAs as for any other borrower at the same credit profile. Physician/Doctor Loan extension rates are typically within 0.125-0.375% of standard pricing in exchange for low-down structure and no PMI. For NPs/PAs with established income tiers, Conventional Conforming or Jumbo at standard rates often prices best.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My productivity bonus runs 15% of total compensation. Does that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; NP/PA productivity bonus or RVU bonus where applicable qualifies as variable income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> with 24-month average plus current-year trending support. RVU bonus structures for NPs and PAs are less universal than for physicians but increasingly common in larger health systems and surgical practice settings.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m an aesthetic medicine NP. How does the practice ownership work for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Aesthetic medicine NP-owned practice operates as S-corp typically, with W-2 reasonable compensation paid to the NP owner plus K-1 distributions of remaining profit. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a>, we aggregate the W-2 plus K-1 distributions with 2-year 1120-S history. Aesthetic medicine equipment (lasers, body sculpting devices) creates Section 179 expensing opportunities that Form 1084 cash-flow analysis recovers for qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My telehealth platform income is from PMHNP psychiatric work at Talkspace. Does that qualify differently?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; PMHNP (Psychiatric Mental Health NP) telehealth platform 1099 income qualifies the same as other NP telehealth income under B3-3.3-02 with 2-year history. Mental health telehealth (Talkspace, Brightside Health, specialty psychiatry platforms) is a growing PMHNP practice area. The qualifying treatment is identical to other specialty NP telehealth.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can a co-borrower help me qualify if my NP income is still ramping?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, significantly. Co-borrower files combine W-2s, 1099s, Schedule C, and S-corp distributions from both parties. For new-grad NPs and PAs in the first 1-2 years where W-2 income is still establishing, a co-borrower with stable W-2 income substantially helps qualifying ratios. Common scenarios: spouse W-2 employment, partner W-2 employment, or parent co-signer.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My CRNA partnership has retained earnings. Are those usable as reserves?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally yes if accessible. Partnership retained earnings in the partnership&rsquo;s business accounts count as reserves if you have the ability to distribute them. Documented via partnership balance sheet on the 1065 return. For established CRNA partners with 5+ years of accumulated retained earnings, the reserve strength supports jumbo qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My state requires a physician collaboration agreement for my NP practice. Does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; collaboration agreements are state scope regulatory requirements, not mortgage qualifying factors. The NP-owned practice S-corp continues to generate W-2 and K-1 income flowing to the NP owner regardless of whether the state requires Full Practice Authority or collaborative agreement structure. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a>, the S-corp distribution is the qualifying income source.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the IRS Section 199A QBI deduction affect my qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Healthcare practice operating including NP/PA practice is generally Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB) under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> with phase-out at $191,950-$241,950 for single filers (2024 indexed). Many NPs and PAs at typical income tiers sit BELOW the phase-out and qualify for the 20% QBI deduction. For practice owner NPs/PAs above the phase-out, the deduction zeroes out. We coordinate with your CPA on documentation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically designed for NPs and PAs?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Physician/Doctor Loan extension to NPs and PAs is the closest specialty product. Beyond that, what matters more is finding a broker who understands B3-3.1-01 hospital W-2 with NP/PA-specific productivity bonus treatment, B3-3.3-02 telehealth platform 1099 aggregation, B3-3.4-02 CRNA partnership K-1 or NP-owned practice S-corp distributions, B3-6-05 IDR documentation for the moderate student loan burden, and the state-specific scope authority context that shapes practice ownership possibilities.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a surgical PA with first-assist income. Does that count separately?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Surgical PA first-assist compensation typically flows through hospital or surgical group W-2 (when employed) or through 1099-NEC if independently contracted with surgical practices. As W-2, first-assist compensation aggregates with primary W-2 under B3-3.1-01 as continuing employment income. As 1099, first-assist income aggregates under B3-3.3-02 as continuing self-employment. Surgical PAs commonly run $165K-$220K total comp through this structure.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My new-grad sign-on bonus is $25K. How does that count for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">$25K single-payment sign-on bonus without continuation provisions may be treated as one-time and excluded from monthly qualifying calculation. Multi-year retention bonuses ($5K-$10K annually across 3-5 years) typically qualify as continuing compensation under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>. We review your contract structure to determine treatment.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My moonlighting at a second clinic adds $35K annually. Will that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes with 2-year history. NP/PA moonlighting W-2 from secondary clinics or hospitals aggregates with primary W-2 under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> as continuing employment income. For NPs/PAs with established 2+ year moonlighting track records, this commonly adds $25K-$60K of qualifying income annually.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 90-120 days before you intend to make an offer. NP/PA files often take longer than standard files because of multi-source income aggregation (W-2 + telehealth + locum + moonlighting), employment contract review for sign-on and loan-repayment treatment, possible S-corp 1120-S review for practice owners, partnership 1065 review for CRNAs, and IDR servicer documentation. For new-grads finishing MSN/DNP or MS-PA programs, starting the conversation in late spring gives proper runway for summer or fall close.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders refuse NP and PA files when there&rsquo;s clearly significant income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Three reasons: (1) generalist lenders don&rsquo;t know which Physician/Doctor Loan programs extend to NPs and PAs, missing the optimal product for the typical income tier; (2) the multi-source income pattern (W-2 + multiple telehealth platforms + locum + moonlighting) gets mis-categorized as &lsquo;contractor work&rsquo; rather than continuing professional self-employment; (3) CRNA partnership K-1 and NP-owned practice S-corp distributions get refused as &lsquo;outside the primary employment&rsquo; rather than properly aggregated under B3-3.4-02. The income is all there and verifiable &mdash; the file just needs a broker who reads NP/PA multi-source structures correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

